  "synthesis": {
    "h1_demographic_amplification": "OCCUPATION-CONDITIONAL. 3 of 13 unique occupations show Bonferroni-significant gender redistribution (alpha=0.05/13=0.0038): teacher (p=1.5e-5, V=0.16), nurse (p=1.6e-4, V=0.14), leader (p=7.1e-4, V=0.13). One borderline at uncorrected: manager (p=0.044). All other occupations (ceo, founder, executive, scientist, doctor, engineer, researcher, programmer, caregiver, receptionist, social_worker) null. Effect is stable across thresholds 5.0/6.0/6.5 (the same baseline vs filtered comparison is preserved across thresholds because we use the SAME baseline subset against three thresholds).",
    "h2_aesthetic_narrowing": "OCCUPATION-CONDITIONAL. Variance-narrowing (var_ratio < 0.7) for: founder, manager, leader, executive, teacher, caregiver, engineer. No narrowing or slight widening (var_ratio >= 0.9) for: ceo (~0.76), nurse (~0.92), doctor (~1.08), scientist (~1.02), programmer (~0.97). Doctor's var_ratio > 1 means filtered subset is MORE variable than baseline — a counter-prediction.",
    "stage_zero_finding": "LAION-2B caption coverage of occupations is itself unequal. Within a 2.5M-row scan (~0.12% of LAION-2B), 'ceo'/'nurse'/'teacher' fill 500/500 buckets cleanly; 'social_worker' (51), 'receptionist' (48), 'researcher' (81), 'programmer' (157), 'caregiver' (133), 'scientist' (327) are partial. The aesthetic-filtered subset is even sparser for those rare categories. The corpus's occupational coverage is itself a stage-prior to RAR's loop and itself stereotype-shaped.",
    "direction_TODO": "p-values and effect sizes are computed; the per-class gender Counter dicts in baseline_gender / filtered_gender (also computed and saved per-occupation CSV in /kaggle/working) determine whether the filter shifts toward or away from the dominant stereotype. Most plausible interpretation given existing literature: filter amplifies stereotypes (more-female teachers/nurses, more-male leaders) — but this should be confirmed by inspecting the CSV files, not assumed."
  }
